There is a problem with Markdown parser. I&#x27;ll show an example to explain it.

{code}
#!markdown
[Bitbucket]: https://bitbucket.org
[Images/Download]: https://bitbucket.org/Haroogan/vim-for-windows/raw/master/images/16-16/download.png "Download"
{code}

*Desired Source:*

{code}
#!markdown

![Download][Images/Download] [Download][Bitbucket]
{code}

*Wrong Result:*

!https://bitbucket.org/Haroogan/vim-for-windows/raw/master/images/16-16/download.png! [Download|https://bitbucket.org]

Current workaround is to trick the parser with some other markup between the image and the hyperlink.

*Workaround Source:*

{code}
#!markdown

![Download][Images/Download]* *[Download][Bitbucket]
{code}

*Correct Result:*

!https://bitbucket.org/Haroogan/vim-for-windows/raw/master/images/16-16/download.png!* *[Download|https://bitbucket.org]

Although there is a workaround, the issue is quite annoying. I hope you can find resources to fix that more or less quickly. Good luck and best regards!

Bitbucket via ssh seems broken, I&#x27;ve the right key loaded but it only works via https

{code}
git pull
conq: repository access denied.
fatal: The remote end hung up unexpectedly
{code}

Symptom: dropdowns not working, like the watching preferences on the top right of a repo page.

Cause: a JS exception in {{opt-store.js}} on line 19 caused the code that handles these things to never run: {{Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read property &#x27;state&#x27; of undefined opt-store.js:19}}

This is the current {{opt-store.js}}:

{code}
#!javascript

define(&#x27;utils/opt-store&#x27;,[
  &#x27;jquery&#x27;,
  &#x27;underscore&#x27;,
  &#x27;data/current-user&#x27;,
  &#x27;data/debug&#x27;,
  &#x27;utils/preferences&#x27;
], function (
  $,
  _,
  currentUser,
  debug,
  preferences
) {

  var
    optimizely = window.optimizely,
    variationMap = {};
  if (!debug && typeof (optimizely) != &#x27;undefined&#x27; && currentUser.isAuthenticated) {
    _.each(optimizely.data.state.activeExperiments, function (id) {
      var variation = optimizely.data.state.variationMap[id];
      preferences.set(&#x27;optimizely-&#x27; + id, variation);
      variationMap[id] = variation;
    });
  }
  return variationMap;

});

{code}

The offending piece is {{optimizely.data.state.activeExperiments}}.

Inspecting the {{window.optimizely}} object one findes that:

* {{optimizely.activeExperiments}} exists and is an empty array ({{[]}})
* the {{optimizely}} object has no other properties.

I guess that this is the result of an API change or something similar, so the way to access the data from that object changed.

One can get around this by putting a breakpoint to a previous line and creating the needed hierarchy of properties on the optimizely object, but it would be good for this to get fixed so one can just click on pieces of UI and have them work :)

Here&#x27;s a [random raw commit|https://bitbucket.org/intgr/pg_journal/commits/fc6d9ee81c812b59dbbbe57c7f22fe3d1b1f1a31/raw/]. Look at the first line. It says:

{code}
#!

From fc6d9ee81c812b59dbbbe57c7f22fe3d1b1f1a31 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
{code}

See the {{Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001}}?\\
There seems to be something wrong with the dates on commits. It says the same date for _all_ commits, too, Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001.

